[Amit Varma]: you're how many episodes already? Mine is, this will be episode 95. Mine is much easier.

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:06.920
[Amit Varma]: You just sit down and you record a conversation. Yours included tons of research and was meticulously

00:04:06.920 --> 00:04:11.160
[Guest]: produced and so on. We had a lot of people interviews from outside etc, which added to

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:15.480
[Amit Varma]: the interest but also made it much harder to do. So what I'd like to do for all of my

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:21.480
[Amit Varma]: listeners who may not know who you are, the few of them, as it might be, is kind of talk

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:25.400
[Amit Varma]: about how you got into writing about food in particular. You're obviously a very accomplished

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:30.440
[Amit Varma]: journalist. You work as a consulting editor at the Economic Times. But what I've always

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:34.280
[Amit Varma]: known you for is for being an incredible food writer. I often tell my friends and I don't

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:37.400
[Amit Varma]: want to embarrass you by saying this, but I often tell people you're the best food writer

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:41.720
[Amit Varma]: in the world because the kind of depth of insights you have not just about food, but

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:47.400
[Amit Varma]: the connections you make with food, to politics, to geography, to culture, to everything just

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:51.880
[Amit Varma]: blows my mind. How did you get interested in food? Well, I mean, when I started off

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:56.200
[Guest]: as a journalist, like a lot of young journalists, you know, all young journalists are made to

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:59.480
[Guest]: do a few routine things, you're always meant to do a few film reviews, you're meant to

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:02.840
[Guest]: do a few book reviews, and you're meant to do a few restaurant reviews. So I started

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:06.760
[Guest]: off doing restaurant reviews for I think it was Business India at that time. And, you

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:10.520
[Guest]: know, very quickly, I got very bored of doing restaurant reviews, because I don't know

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:15.480
[Guest]: if you agree with me, but I find the restaurant scene in Bombay is pretty sad. And for a basic

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.560
[Guest]: economic reason, I mean, the rents in Bombay are so high, the overheads for restaurants

00:05:19.560 --> 00:05:23.720
[Guest]: are so high, that it pretty much kills off any interesting restaurant, you know, all

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:28.600
[Guest]: restaurants to make money have to become a sort of mean level food that they produce

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:33.800
[Guest]: really interesting niche restaurants. It's happening now, to some extent, but like 20

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:39.960
[Guest]: years back, it was pretty rare. And this is early 90s. Yeah, it was mid 90s. And, you

00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:45.880
[Guest]: know, around that time, I mean, and I quickly ran through all the interesting niche restaurants

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:51.720
[Guest]: in Bombay. And I got really bored. And also beyond the point, I started appreciating what

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:57.720
[Guest]: goes into producing restaurants, and the amount of effort that people, you know, put into

00:05:57.720 --> 00:06:02.280
[Guest]: running restaurants is crazy. And I started feeling guilty beyond the point of just coming

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:06.840
[Guest]: and having one meal and writing some stupid review about that. I mean, I'm not saying

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:10.360
[Guest]: all the restaurants were good. Many of them were completely crappy. But even a crappy

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:15.720
[Guest]: restaurant, unfortunately, requires a lot of work. So I just got bored about writing

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:21.000
[Guest]: about restaurants. But I did discover something interesting that I could talk to anyone about

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:26.120
[Guest]: food. And you could strike up a conversation. It's very, very rare that you find someone

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:31.080
[Guest]: who is not interested with food. And also, what was interesting about food was that you

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:36.760
[Guest]: could talk to people who people don't normally talk to. So for instance, women, a lot of

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:42.840
[Guest]: older women, you know, people who work behind the scenes, everybody's interested in food,

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:48.040
[Guest]: everybody has food stories. Everybody has food memories. It became a great way to learn

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:52.840
[Amit Varma]: about people and different aspects of India. And were you interested in food in a general

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:56.760
[Amit Varma]: way from before this? Because you know, the depth of knowledge that you show in your columns,

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:01.000
[Amit Varma]: for example, when you go to the origins of different kinds of food, and you're practically

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.480
[Amit Varma]: going back hundreds of years and drawing all these intricate narratives? How do you gain

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:08.760
[Amit Varma]: that knowledge? I mean, part of it, of course, comes from talking to people, like you said,

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:12.840
[Guest]: part of it comes from talking to people, but also a lot of it comes from just reading material.

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:19.160
[Guest]: I was always interested in history. And especially, you know, different sources of history,

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:24.280
[Guest]: like personal memoirs, newspaper accounts, you know, these sources of history that often get

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:29.480
[Guest]: overlooked. And I found that there was a wealth of material in that, which people were just not

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:34.040
[Guest]: looking at. There were all sorts of unusual sources of information, you know, for instance,

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:38.840
[Guest]: especially when it comes to food. One of the things people don't understand about the government,

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:43.880
[Guest]: especially, you know, the agricultural department, is that we have this vast network of agricultural

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:49.880
[Guest]: research institutes, almost any type of food of any type of agricultural issue, there's an

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:54.440
[Guest]: institute dedicated to that, who are doing all sorts of fascinating in depth research in these

00:07:54.440 --> 00:08:00.120
[Guest]: areas. And you can often write to the directors of these institutes. And you'll get fascinating

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:04.280
[Guest]: bits of information, you know, so I started, you know, one thing I'm particularly interested in is

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:10.280
[Guest]: bananas, partly because I'm from South India, and I've always liked bananas. And I started becoming

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:14.840
[Guest]: curious about the different types of bananas I would see on the street side, especially in South

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:19.000
[Guest]: India, and I didn't know the names, or they had, you know, different names. And I started trying to

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.600
[Guest]: identify these bananas. And I actually wrote to the director of the National Research Center for

00:08:22.600 --> 00:08:28.600
[Guest]: bananas in Trichy, a very nice gentleman called Dr. Mustafa at that time and sending him pictures

00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:33.240
[Guest]: of the bananas, and he would very sweetly like, identify them and tell me a bit more about them.

00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:38.280
[Guest]: And that's when I realized that the stories behind things are really fascinating. And it's all there,

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:42.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, just you just have to read about it. And I mean, just hearing about a National

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:48.920
[Amit Varma]: Research Center for bananas is kind of funny in itself. So you know, the way I've always sort of

00:08:48.920 --> 00:08:54.280
[Amit Varma]: food is I kind of think of food and cuisines as a static kind of thing, that I know that, okay,

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:59.240
[Amit Varma]: this is Konkani cuisine, and this is Tamilian cuisine, and this is North Indian cuisine,

00:08:59.240 --> 00:09:04.440
[Amit Varma]: and blah, blah, blah. And, and that's partly because I'm at this fixed point in time,

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:09.320
[Amit Varma]: and I'm looking at it from that vantage point. And the more you read, and especially you get a

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:14.120
[Amit Varma]: sense of this through reading your columns, that it's actually really dynamic. And a lot of what

00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:19.640
[Amit Varma]: we think of as Indian food isn't really Indian at all. In fact, there's so much of an intermingling

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:25.720
[Amit Varma]: of cultures and traditions in this almost literal and metaphorical melting pot, so to say.

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:30.920
[Guest]: Absolutely. And, you know, I mean, I think this is true of any country, but particularly India,

00:09:30.920 --> 00:09:34.760
[Guest]: because, you know, this was one country where so many different traditions, so many

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:39.720
[Guest]: trade routes would meet. I mean, you know, we were at one end of the Silk Road,

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:45.320
[Guest]: there's so many spices came, not just from India, but from Southeast Asia through India. So, you

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:49.800
[Guest]: know, that gave us all the connections towards Southeast Asia. So then you had all the different

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:55.240
[Guest]: waves of colonists and, you know, other people coming into India, bringing their own food

00:09:55.240 --> 00:10:01.640
[Guest]: traditions, refugees, immigrants. There's always been this vast churn of people across India,

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:07.720
[Guest]: and each churn is accompanied by their own food traditions. So that's what's really fascinating.

00:10:07.720 --> 00:10:11.800
[Guest]: There's nothing, once you start reading Indian food traditions, you realize that nothing is

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:17.320
[Guest]: static, that some of the things that we think are most intrinsically Indian are actually not

00:10:17.320 --> 00:10:22.120
[Guest]: that Indian in their origin, though we have made them Indian now. And I'll give you two

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:26.840
[Guest]: fascinating examples. You know, we're recording this in November, the, you know, the festive

00:10:26.840 --> 00:10:32.040
[Guest]: Diwali has just got over. And we have seen like all the religious seasons, all the rituals have

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:35.880
[Guest]: been happening. And you know, we've all these rituals have been accompanied by marigolds. And

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.480
[Guest]: we think of marigolds as being one of the most intrinsically Indian flowers.

00:10:41.480 --> 00:10:42.520
[Guest]: This is Gandalful.

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:45.480
[Guest]: Gandalful, yeah, which you can eat, by the way. So I'm not actually,

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:49.800
[Guest]: if you remember in Monsoon Wedding, there was that guy who was always eating the marigolds. So

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:54.920
[Guest]: I'm not drifting too far away from food. Now, what people don't understand is that the marigolds that

00:10:54.920 --> 00:11:00.840
[Guest]: we have today are actually not Indian in origin. They are Mexican marigolds. They're a type of

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:06.040
[Guest]: plant called tagetes, which actually there was an Indian marigold earlier, which some people still

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:11.880
[Guest]: grow. They're called calendulas. They both have the same bright orange color. But calendulas are

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:17.160
[Guest]: simpler flowers, whereas the Mexican marigolds are much more impressive looking flowers.

00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:23.240
[Guest]: And at some point, these Mexican marigolds came to India. And we quietly shifted to growing

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:27.960
[Guest]: marigolds, which have always been part of Indian tradition, but just growing these Mexican

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:33.000
[Guest]: marigolds. So to me, it's fascinating, this Indian, all these Indian festivals are happening

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.120
[Guest]: with Mexican marigolds.

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:36.760
[Guest]: Right. And what about the other one?

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:40.680
[Guest]: The other one is actually saffron. I mean, and I don't want to get too political, but you know,

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:46.120
[Guest]: the way saffron is now used as an adjective for a particular type of politics. And we say saffron

00:11:46.120 --> 00:11:52.760
[Guest]: this, saffron like, saffron activists. But saffron in itself is not Indian. Now, let me qualify that.

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:59.560
[Guest]: What is deeply Indian, what is deeply Hindu is that orange color. That orange color has always

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:04.680
[Guest]: been an intrinsically important part of Hindu rituals. And that would have come from, you know,

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:09.720
[Guest]: ochre in the earth or from turmeric in particular. Turmeric is deeply Indian. It's a deeply Indian

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:16.840
[Guest]: part of Indian rituals. But saffron is not. I mean, saffron is an interesting spice for a couple

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:22.680
[Guest]: of reasons. One is it's a spice from the temperate zones. We think of spices as coming from tropical

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:27.160
[Guest]: countries, but saffron actually comes from the crocus flower, which grows in temperate climates.

00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:32.040
[Guest]: So it's one of the rare spices which comes from the more northern latitudes, which means that

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:38.120
[Guest]: there's only one part of India which is suitable for it, which is actually Kashmir. So and the

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:46.120
[Guest]: saffron in Kashmir is only recorded from around about the 5th or 6th century AD. So saffron in

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:52.200
[Guest]: itself is not deeply Indian. What seems to have happened, and unfortunately, as with a lot of food

00:12:52.200 --> 00:13:00.040
[Guest]: stuff, a lot of it is just conjecture. We started using kesar as an indication for that orange color,

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:05.720
[Guest]: which was so deeply Indian, possibly because it was more expensive. It was a sort of aspirational,

00:13:05.720 --> 00:13:12.200
[Guest]: you know, it was more aspirational than haldi. So now we use kesar as a synonym for a whole

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:17.800
[Guest]: type of Hinduism. But saffron is not Indian. So where did it come from? It probably came from

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:21.640
[Guest]: somewhere in the Middle East, from somewhere in Turkey or somewhere like that, which is an

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:27.880
[Guest]: area of a lot of biodiversity. What else came from there? Oh, so much. I mean, wheat, of course,

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:34.040
[Guest]: originally came from there, possibly a whole bunch of spices like coriander, cumin.

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:41.080
[Guest]: Rotis are not Indian. Well, yeah, rotis are probably not Indian. And in fact, through large

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:45.640
[Guest]: parts of India, they have not been part of Indian culture for very long. I mean, especially if you

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:51.000
[Guest]: come from South India, where I grew up, wheat, bread, rotis was simply not part of the culture.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:56.600
[Guest]: I mean, there were a few communities that made wheat rotis. But it really, wheat started growing

00:13:56.600 --> 00:14:03.480
[Guest]: in South India after the 60s for a very simple economic political reason. In the 60s, India was

00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:08.920
[Guest]: suffering from really severe famines. And we approached the US for aid, which the US under

00:14:08.920 --> 00:14:13.720
[Guest]: Lyndon Johnson gave us aid, but as always with Americans, it was aid on their terms, which means

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:19.160
[Guest]: they didn't give us money, they gave us grain, the vast amounts of wheat grown in the Midwestern

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:25.880
[Guest]: states. So we got wheat under the PL 480 program. But once it came to India, the government had to

00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:31.400
[Guest]: make Indians eat it. And we weren't used to this. I mean, for one thing, it was a very different

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:35.720
[Guest]: type of wheat from the sort of wheat that was being eaten in North India. You have lots of

00:14:35.720 --> 00:14:40.760
[Guest]: complaints from the era of people in North India who had to like suddenly start eating this hard

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:44.840
[Guest]: American wheat. And then it had to come to South India where there were no traditions at all.

00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:50.440
[Guest]: And through a process of, you know, commercial spreading through sheer necessity through

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:55.800
[Guest]: government promotion, South India slowly started eating wheat. And so now it's very common in South

00:14:55.800 --> 00:15:00.920
[Guest]: India to have bread and rotis and malabar parathas and things like that. But it's something which is

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:04.280
[Amit Varma]: less than 50 years old. And that's quite mind blowing to me, because of malabar paratha or the

00:15:04.280 --> 00:15:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Kerala paratha, you think, oh, this is obviously so Indian as part of that cuisine. And you're

00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:12.760
[Guest]: pointing out that it's not even as old as Nehru. Absolutely. I mean, a Kerala in particular,

00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:16.920
[Guest]: and I'm saying this, because I'm half a Malayali has always been in a state where we just seen a

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:22.120
[Guest]: real wide amount of change of new products being introduced. And some of them are actually very

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:27.080
[Guest]: precisely dated, for instance, tapioca kappa, which is now seen as such a Malayali thing,

00:15:27.080 --> 00:15:31.720
[Guest]: you can go to Malayali restaurants and you have kappa biryani and kappa and fish curry.

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:38.280
[Guest]: But kappa, tapioca was very consciously introduced by the king of Travancore sometime in the mid

00:15:38.280 --> 00:15:45.800
[Guest]: 19th century, when he saw that he needed some sort of starch substitute to make up for the rice

00:15:45.800 --> 00:15:50.120
[Guest]: deficiencies because of shortfalls in rice production. And he realized that tapioca was

00:15:50.120 --> 00:15:56.280
[Guest]: a tropical plant that grew easily. And he very consciously introduced tapioca into Kerala.

00:15:56.280 --> 00:15:59.480
[Guest]: And now tapioca is seen as intrinsically part of Kerala culture.

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:02.680
[Amit Varma]: And this was a king of Travancore. But before that, where did tapioca come from?

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:05.720
[Guest]: Tapioca, cassava comes from the new world from Brazil.

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:10.520
[Amit Varma]: Right, from South America, from South America. So just to sort of go back to that earlier thing,

00:16:10.520 --> 00:16:14.840
[Amit Varma]: which we digress from, which is a Middle East. So what else comes from the wheat you were saying

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:22.360
[Guest]: comes from there, as you said, saffron, a whole range of spices, a number of fruits, lemons,

00:16:22.360 --> 00:16:26.280
[Guest]: things like that. The Middle East is one of the great centers of biodiversity.

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:29.800
[Amit Varma]: And from there, not just ingredients, but we also had ways of cooking and

00:16:29.800 --> 00:16:31.800
[Guest]: entire cuisines come from the Middle East.

00:16:31.800 --> 00:16:36.280
[Guest]: Yes, to some extent. I mean, you know, for instance, a lot of our traditions of frying

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:39.880
[Guest]: and deep frying do seem to have come from the Middle East. And there are a number of reasons

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:44.920
[Guest]: for this. I mean, while, you know, I don't want to generalize and saying that frying was not

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:50.040
[Guest]: there in India earlier. It's true that frying was not common, as far as we know,

00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:54.680
[Guest]: from the earlier sources. And there's a very simple reason for that. It's the fuel sources.

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:59.000
[Guest]: I mean, a lot of food and cooking is driven by what fuel is available at your disposal.

00:16:59.560 --> 00:17:05.800
[Guest]: And in India, we did not have many fuel sources. Coal was relatively unknown in India. In fact,

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:10.600
[Guest]: it was completely unknown until the British era, except in very small parts of the Northeast.

00:17:10.600 --> 00:17:14.920
[Guest]: There was wood, but then wood has always been a problem through large parts of India.

00:17:14.920 --> 00:17:20.040
[Guest]: Our basic fuel source was cow dung. And it's one reason, among many others, that, you know,

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:24.840
[Guest]: cows are given this very special status in India. And if you know anything about cow dung,

00:17:24.840 --> 00:17:29.880
[Guest]: is it burns with a very slow flame, okay? You can't get a very high heat on cow dung.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:34.440
[Guest]: What it's ideal for is for boiling. So, we developed whole cuisines based essentially

00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:39.400
[Guest]: around boiling foods and our pots also became pots that could go on cow dung fires.

00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:44.200
[Guest]: So, there is some truth in the point that people like Michael Pollan have made that,

00:17:44.200 --> 00:17:51.080
[Guest]: you know, Indian cuisine is essentially in its origins about boiling. But once the Muslims come

00:17:51.080 --> 00:17:55.960
[Guest]: in, and these traditions come in, you get much many more traditions of frying. In fact, in many

00:17:55.960 --> 00:18:02.040
[Guest]: parts of India, frying is still seen as much more of a Muslim tradition. And a lot of the utensils,

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:07.000
[Guest]: for instance, copper, which is ideal for frying because it conducts heat fast, is again seen as a

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:12.200
[Guest]: utensil as a type of metal used in the Muslim tradition. And again, we get, you know, many

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:16.600
[Guest]: types of food. So, one of the most intrinsic foods to India, which we think is so Indian,

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:21.080
[Guest]: as samosas, I mean, you know, you remember, what was the line that Lalu Prasad used?

00:18:21.080 --> 00:18:25.240
[Amit Varma]: Jab tak samosa mein rahega, aloo Bihar mein rahega.

00:18:25.240 --> 00:18:29.720
[Guest]: Now, what is fascinating about that is neither samosas or aloo are originally Indian. Okay,

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:33.640
[Guest]: potatoes come with the British, samosas come from probably the Turkish tradition,

00:18:33.640 --> 00:18:37.960
[Guest]: where you have something called sambusak. And this idea of getting a wheat dough,

00:18:37.960 --> 00:18:42.760
[Guest]: which is kneaded with oil, so it becomes flaky. That's a very intrinsically part of Turkic culture.

00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:47.080
[Guest]: You see it throughout Central Asia, and down to Turkey, where you have sambusak.

00:18:47.720 --> 00:18:53.640
[Guest]: So, samosas and potatoes are, you know, something that have come to us from outside and this

00:18:53.640 --> 00:18:58.440
[Amit Varma]: tradition of, of cooking of deep frying things. Fantastic. And you know, one of the points you

00:18:58.440 --> 00:19:03.160
[Amit Varma]: made to me when we were talking just before we started the recording for the show is that a lot

00:19:03.160 --> 00:19:09.240
[Amit Varma]: of Indian cooking has adapted itself by pragmatism. And therefore, a lot of foreign

00:19:09.240 --> 00:19:13.240
[Amit Varma]: elements get easily adapted, because they just happen to be more suited. Can you elaborate?

00:19:13.240 --> 00:19:19.160
[Guest]: Yeah, see, I mean, this is a point, I think, a very pragmatic point that I often emphasize that,

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:24.280
[Guest]: you know, when it comes to cooking, we often forget who is actually doing the cooking.

00:19:24.280 --> 00:19:29.800
[Guest]: And the truth of Indian cooking is that vast amounts of Indian cooking depends on the

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:33.960
[Guest]: unacknowledged labor of two types of people, servants and daughters-in-law,

00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:39.640
[Guest]: who are treated as servants, essentially. And this labor, you know, this unacknowledged labor

00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:45.240
[Guest]: is what really goes into creating food, Indian food, and it's their labor, which would do all

00:19:45.240 --> 00:19:50.520
[Guest]: this really boring, messy, tedious stuff that went into a lot of traditional cooking.

00:19:51.160 --> 00:19:57.000
[Guest]: And nobody wants to do this sort of work. So, as you know, more people became empowered,

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:01.080
[Guest]: as it became harder to force, you know, your daughters-in-law to work as like,

00:20:01.640 --> 00:20:05.640
[Guest]: essentially slave labor, people stopped wanting to do this traditional food. So,

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:10.600
[Guest]: I'll give you one example. One type of food that is very essentially Indian, in fact,

00:20:10.600 --> 00:20:17.080
[Guest]: is banana flowers. Okay. Mochar, as you know them in Bengal, and it was there right through

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:22.760
[Guest]: southern India, through Bengal. In fact, if you can go to books like the Supershastra,

00:20:22.760 --> 00:20:27.080
[Guest]: which is from something I'm forgetting that actually dates, but from Karnataka, it's an amazing

00:20:27.080 --> 00:20:31.560
[Guest]: book. It's a cookbook, which half the recipes are using banana flower in different ways. And,

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:35.320
[Guest]: you know, when you look at this at the recipes, they're fascinating recipes from historical

00:20:35.320 --> 00:20:39.880
[Guest]: perspective. But I just keep thinking of all the people who had to clean the banana flowers.

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:45.480
[Guest]: And if you've ever cleaned banana flowers, you will know it's a tedious job, because you have

00:20:45.480 --> 00:20:49.240
[Guest]: to oil your hands, because there's a sort of sticky substance that's in the banana flowers.

00:20:49.240 --> 00:20:54.360
[Guest]: And then each petal, you know, each sort of proto banana has this sort of undigestible part,

00:20:54.360 --> 00:20:58.920
[Guest]: which has to be cleaned off by hand. It's a real pain. You've cleaned it. I've tried doing it,

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:04.040
[Guest]: and it's a real pain. I mean, the results are delicious. I love mochar. I love the banana

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:08.920
[Guest]: flower recipes once they finally cook, but God knows it's not something I want to do every day.

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:15.800
[Guest]: And so, at some point, when these English vegetables, as they're called foreign vegetables

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:21.480
[Guest]: started coming in from different sources, people stopped cooking banana flower. And they start

00:21:21.480 --> 00:21:25.720
[Guest]: cook to these sort of Western vegetables, or not Western, just from outside India,

00:21:25.720 --> 00:21:31.000
[Guest]: non-Indian vegetables, which were just much easier to cook. Cabbage, for instance, you know,

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:35.320
[Guest]: I mean, you can cook red cabbage in particular, so that it tastes a lot like banana flower.

00:21:35.320 --> 00:21:39.560
[Guest]: And it's so much easier to cook. You just chop it up. I mean, cabbage is not Indian,

00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:44.600
[Guest]: it's a very deeply European vegetable. But I often think Indians cook cabbage in really

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:48.920
[Guest]: wonderful ways. It's just that because we don't value cabbage, we don't value all the Indian

00:21:48.920 --> 00:21:55.800
[Guest]: dishes that use cabbage. So, we started cooking all these vegetables. And these sort of traditional

00:21:55.800 --> 00:22:00.920
[Guest]: Indian vegetables got largely forgotten. I mean, the interesting irony is that these

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:07.640
[Guest]: vegetables are now being rediscovered, not in India, but abroad, because the huge growth of

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:13.800
[Guest]: the vegan movement abroad is actually finding all these traditional Indian ingredients very useful,

00:22:13.800 --> 00:22:18.200
[Guest]: because so much of Indian food is actually very easily adaptable to vegan food, especially from

00:22:18.200 --> 00:22:22.680
[Guest]: South India, where you have coconut milk, instead of cow's milk or buffalo's milk,

00:22:22.680 --> 00:22:28.440
[Guest]: then it's all essentially vegan food. So, you can go to New York, and you can have these really

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:34.200
[Guest]: fancy hipster restaurants, which will serve you burgers made out of banana flower, or green jack

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:39.080
[Guest]: fruit, another very intrinsically Indian vegetable. Whereas it's almost impossible to get these dishes

00:22:39.080 --> 00:22:43.480
[Amit Varma]: in India now, for good reason. And you know, a few episodes back, I did an episode of the

00:22:43.480 --> 00:22:47.880
[Amit Varma]: scene in the unseen called metrics of empowerment, where I sat down with three economists, Devika

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:52.200
[Amit Varma]: Kher, Nidhi Gupta, and Hamsini Hariharan, and we were trying to figure out some sort of out of the

00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:56.520
[Amit Varma]: box metrics, which showed that women have been empowered. And you know, the image that you

00:22:56.520 --> 00:23:02.520
[Amit Varma]: painted of a male patriarch ordering ki, you know, give me mochad dalna and somebody has to and then

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:07.880
[Amit Varma]: the daughter in law has to clean the banana flower. And but gradually over the ages, as those daughters

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:11.960
[Amit Varma]: in law become more empowered and can put their foot down, they choose to make cabbage instead.

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:16.440
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, one offbeat metric of empowerment is a move away from banana flower to cabbage.

00:23:16.440 --> 00:23:19.640
[Guest]: Oh, actually, you know, one of the best examples is something that has happened,

00:23:19.640 --> 00:23:22.680
[Guest]: maybe if not in our generation, but in our parents generation,

00:23:22.680 --> 00:23:26.440
[Guest]: which is the great shift to stainless steel. I mean, I don't know if you remember this,

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:31.240
[Guest]: but I do remember like, you know, these these women would come to the houses with these with

00:23:31.240 --> 00:23:35.080
[Guest]: these stainless steel vessels, they were these sort of nomadic women. And they would ask the

00:23:35.080 --> 00:23:40.040
[Guest]: women if they had like old saris, which had zari in them. And it was amazing, like how many women

00:23:40.040 --> 00:23:45.000
[Guest]: would empty out their chest full of saris and exchange them for these stainless steel vessels.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:50.840
[Guest]: And in a matter of about a decade, stainless steel, which was a very niche product, it was,

00:23:50.840 --> 00:23:55.640
[Guest]: you know, originally used for making armaments. Stainless steel became ubiquitous in Indian

00:23:55.640 --> 00:23:59.160
[Guest]: kitchens for us today, many of us when we think of traditional Indian kitchens,

00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:03.240
[Guest]: we think of stainless steel, all that bright silver, ever silver, it was called

00:24:03.240 --> 00:24:07.480
[Guest]: stainless steel vessels, and you know, shops full of stainless steel vessels. But this happened in

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:12.920
[Guest]: a matter of 10 years. And why did it happen? It's not even that stainless steel is a particularly

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:15.960
[Guest]: good medium for cooking, it's actually not a particularly good medium, because it doesn't

00:24:15.960 --> 00:24:21.400
[Guest]: conduct heat very well. Things like brass and copper are actually much better conductors of

00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:27.720
[Guest]: heat. But stainless steel is easy to clean. And if you've ever been through the trouble of

00:24:27.720 --> 00:24:32.840
[Guest]: cleaning brass vessels, you know what a pain it is. I mean, to clean brass vessels properly,

00:24:32.840 --> 00:24:37.880
[Guest]: you need something acidic. So you had these sort of, you know, solutions of tamarind, we had to

00:24:37.880 --> 00:24:42.360
[Guest]: steep and then you had to clean it. And then once or twice every year, you had to get the kalaiwala

00:24:42.360 --> 00:24:46.520
[Guest]: to come. I don't know if you've ever seen that the guys would come and make little fires outside

00:24:46.520 --> 00:24:52.680
[Guest]: your house and put the tin lining inside. Taking care of brass vessels is a real pain, they're also

00:24:52.680 --> 00:25:00.280
[Guest]: like really heavy. So within 10 years, women in the kitchen, very happily gave up all their

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:06.600
[Guest]: traditional brass vessels for stainless steel. And that's actually a marvellous heading for the

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:11.320
[Amit Varma]: journey that the Indian woman has taken from saris to stainless steel, absolutely beautiful

00:25:11.320 --> 00:25:15.160
[Amit Varma]: alliterations. We'll take a quick commercial break here. And we'll talk more about Indian

